ntiments in Mexico. This book examines the response of Mexican immigrants to Anglo American prejudice and violence early in the twentieth century. Drawing on archival sources from both sides of the border, Arturo Rosales traces the rise of "México Lindo" nationalism and the efforts of Mexican consuls to help poor Mexican immigrants defend themselves against abuses and flagrant civil rights violations by Anglo citizens, police, and the U.S. judicial system. This research illuminates a dark era in which civilian and police brutality, prejudice in the courtroom, and disproportionate arrest, conviction, and capital punishment rates too often characterized justice for Mexican Americans.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aDiscrimination in criminal justice administrationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aImmigrants - Civil rights - United States. 0aImmigrantsxCivil rightszUnited States. 0aMexicansxCivil rightszUnited States. 0aMexicansxCrimes againstzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292799356423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292799356/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK